# {title}

`tokenizeTarget(text: string): TargetToken[]` ‚Äî in `src/lib/tokenize.ts` ‚Äî turns the English translation into an array of [[data-and-tokenization/tokens|target tokens]] (`TargetToken[]`).

## Why this is the hard tokenizer

On the source side, "one character = one token" is unambiguous. The target side is where it gets interesting. The user thinks in **words**, but English text is riddled with punctuation that is sometimes part of a word (`don't`, `programming.`) and sometimes its own thing (`well-known` is two mappable halves and a hyphen; an em-dash sits between two words). Get this wrong and either punctuation becomes its own confusing clickable fragment, or two things that should be separately mappable get stuck together.

So the tokenizer follows one guiding rule: **punctuation that touches a word is absorbed into that word, but punctuation wedged *between* two word-characters splits out** ‚Äî so each piece stays individually mappable.

## How it works

A single regex, `TARGET_RE`, matches in priority order:

1. a single Han character;
2. a word (Latin letters / digits) with any *flanking* punctuation absorbed;
3. a whitespace run (excluding newlines);
4. a standalone punctuation run not adjacent to any word.

```
There's nothing "simple" in programming.
‚Üí [There's][ ][nothing][ ]["simple"][ ][in][ ][programming.]
```

### The merge rules, by example

- **Flanking punctuation is absorbed** into the word it touches: `"simple"`, `programming.`, `(hello)`, `$5`, `5%`.
- **Interior punctuation splits out** ‚Äî punctuation with word-characters on *both* sides becomes its own token: `well-known` ‚Üí `[well][-][known]`; `3.14` ‚Üí `[3][.][14]`; `$5,000.00` ‚Üí `[$5][,][000][.][00]`. This is what makes hyphenated compounds and multi-part numbers mappable piece by piece.
- **Contractions are the one exception** to "interior splits out" ‚Äî a straight `'` or curly `'` apostrophe between word-characters stays merged: `don't`, `it's`, `dogs'` (the regex carries an explicit `(?:['']‚Ä¶)*` group for exactly this case).
- **Standalone punctuation** with no adjacent word is its own token: `...`, or an em-dash between words (`word‚Äîword` ‚Üí `[word][‚Äî][word]`).
- **Han characters in target text** stay single-character tokens, same as the source side; adjacent punctuation stays standalone (`‰ΩÝÂ•Ω!` ‚Üí `[‰ΩÝ][Â•Ω][!]`).

The interior-versus-flanking distinction is enforced by lookbehind / lookahead assertions (`(?<![A-Za-z0-9])` / `(?![A-Za-z0-9])`) around word characters, and the whole behavior is pinned down by an extensive set of cases in `src/lib/vitest-examples/tokenize.spec.ts`.

> **History:** earlier versions had two separate target tokenizers ‚Äî `tokenizeTargetSeparate` and `tokenizeTargetCombined` ‚Äî for two slightly different needs. They were consolidated into this single `tokenizeTarget` so the rest of the app only ever has to reason about one shape of `TargetToken[]`.

### Token types

| Type | When |
|------|------|
| `'whitespace'` | a whitespace run |
| `'hanzi'` | a single Han character |
| `'text'` | any token containing a letter or digit (`[\p{L}\p{N}]`) ‚Äî so `$5` and `simple.` are `'text'` and therefore mappable |
| `'punctuation'` | a pure-symbol run |

## Line stamping and the boundary whitespace token

Like the source tokenizer, this one splits on `\n` and stamps each token with its segment's `line` index, consuming the newline itself.

Additionally, after the tokens of each line ‚Äî but **not** after the last one ‚Äî a synthetic boundary token is appended:

```ts
if (line < lines.length - 1) tokens.push({ text: ' ', line, type: 'whitespace' });
```

This token has no counterpart in the real text. Its job is purely interactive: in [[interaction-modes/line-mode|Line mode]] clicking it merges the two lines it sits between. See [[interaction-modes/line-mode#the-line-tool-affordances]].

## Whitespace strategy

Whitespace tokens exist in the target stream, but they are deliberately *not* full participants in the alignment:

- **Not interactive in Link mode** ‚Äî `toggleTarget` early-returns for whitespace (and punctuation), so they can never start or join a mapping.
- **Never stored in a mapping** ‚Äî no [[data-and-tokenization/mapping|`Mapping`]] will ever hold a whitespace token's ID.
- **Visually bridged** ‚Äî a whitespace token flanked on both sides by tokens from the *same* mapping inherits that mapping's color, so a multi-word phrase reads as one continuous highlight rather than a striped one. See [[interaction-modes/link-mode#whitespace-bridging]].
- **Bridged in exported text** ‚Äî when building the readable text for a mapping, short gaps (‚â§ 5 tokens, all whitespace/punctuation) are treated as contiguous, so the mapping's text renders as a single phrase instead of comma-joined fragments.
- **Still copyable** ‚Äî in Line mode, whitespace tokens render as `<span role="button">` rather than `<button>`, with `user-select: text`, so selecting and copying the target text still includes the spaces.

Source tokens never have a whitespace type ‚Äî the source input filter strips spaces entirely before tokenization ever sees them.
